{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1948"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1948"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.16,0.22,0.35,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1948"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32542"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1948"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1948"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18117"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"2108"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3661"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44063"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32542"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 7-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her parents. They live rurally on a farm. Her parents report that the child has had a one week history of bloody diarrhoea. She is feeling very tired, and has not passed urine for the past 24 hours. Prior to this, she would infrequently pass urine and this was dark in colour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her temperature is 36.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, pulse rate 142/min, and blood pressure 110/85mmHg. She is pale and quiet with rapid deep breathing. She has sunken eyes and a central capillary refill time of four seconds. She has numerous ecchymoses, and non-blanching, non-palpable petechiae over her lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigation results is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prolonged prothrombin and partial thromboplastin times","Isolated thrombocytopaenia","Raised serum IgA","Positive stool PCR for E. coli","Increased haptoglobin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation in a young girl, of bloody diarrhoea, anaemia, non-palpable petechiae and acute renal failure is consistent with haemolytic uraemic syndrome. This syndrome is most commonly caused by enterohaemorrhagic Escherichia coli (EHEC) and its Shiga toxin. In 5-15% of children affected with EHEC dysentery, the Shiga toxin enters the blood stream, binds to receptors sites at target organs, resulting in endothelial damage. This damaged endothelium leads to thrombus formation, which can cause ischaemia to end organs, particularly the kidney, and shred passing erythrocytes, causing a microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia. As platelets are consumed a thrombocytopaenia develops. \u003Cstrong\u003EStool is likely to be positive for E.coli\u003C/strong\u003E. Most stool tests are PCR based. They proceed to culture only if the PCR for common pathogens is positive. Culture is then used for antibiotic sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coagulation factors themselves are unaffected (and would be normal) \u2013 they would be altered in disseminated intravascular coagulation. An isolated thrombocytopaenia would be the case in immune thrombocytopaenic purpura. Raised serum IgA might be present in Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura vasculitis, in addition to palpable purpura. Haptoglobin would be lowered as it binds to the haemoglobin now in the serum with erythrocyte haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Always consider checking renal function in a child presenting with bloody diarrhoea and petechiae"],"references":["Canpolat N. Hemolytic uremic syndrome. Turk Pediatri Ars. 2015;50(2):73-82.","Tarr PI, Gordon CA, Chandler WL. Shiga-toxin-producing Escherichia coli and haemolytic uraemic syndrome. Lancet. 2005;365(9464):1073-1086.","Fakhouri F, Zuber J, Fr\u00e9meaux-Bacchi V, Loirat C. Haemolytic uraemic syndrome [published correction appears in Lancet]. 2017 Aug"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18117"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1948"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18117"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-15T18:35:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-02-15T18:35:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1948"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32542"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"